title: How to Build Your Ultimate Productivity System
split_comments: 11:06 aaaahh if this phrase was only a hyperbole... but it literally happened to me, and i think it will never be "cured", is just how the brain is programmed. i think i've memorized the obstacle is the way almost entirely, everytime i ready it feels familiar and i know the next phrase likes pieces falling perfectly in place in a cascade (especially if i reread a couple of times after a layoff) but the problem is: i can't remember by my own! everything comes fluidly reading out loud but if i had to recite from heart i would suddenly forget big chunks of it.if you ever did singing classes - or simply sang with the music - you know how much more easier it to find the tone when the song is on or there's a coach is doing with you, but once he/she asks you to go by yourself... *gulp* you're in a bit of a pickle. that's because doing by yourself is much more harder and weaknesses of yours are exposed, you naturally start to notice things about yourself, about your pattern of thinking and your technique that you don't notice normally, there's much more presence and self awareness.after using active recall in past few months i realized how much more different it is from passively reading, there's a more intense "imagery", you have to use much more brain power to remember and at times feels like you are physically exerting yourself to pull something. but your ideas feels more powerful, permanent, and this different feeling gives you confidence that you don't get with the old way (it's kinda common sense to be honest, like the principle of specificity in power/olyliftiing). if you ever played chess you had a similar feeling of mentally exausting but this also make you remember and progress surprinsingly faster."to get stronger you have to compete" as everyone in chess says,  they knew the nature of learning for a loooong time.

title: 5 Essential Tips for Long-Lasting Productivity
split_comments: i could've helped him discover this a long time ago :face_with_tears_of_joy: after watching several of his videos i definitely started to see that while there are a lot of gidgits, gadgets, and gizmos-- they aren't all necessary. i also started to wonder how much those apps might start getting in the way of actually getting things done. yeah, you have an app that saves articles for later, but that doesn't mean it helps you get through the goal of actually reading the articles you save. to-do lists can be beneficial, but use them too rigidly; you won't want to do anything. being productive definitely comes from an aspirational mindset, and using some (but probably not all) of the widgets can make a dredging experience more novel. that helps you get engaged with the task. those things we don't actually want to do since we are cognitive misers and don't want to expend our mental faculties will probably benefit from a written goal with tangible evidence of completion (e.g., checking it off the list).simply put, you need two big things for productivity-- goals and habits. if you want to become productive, you need to set small goals that encourage your progression to a larger purpose, and you need good habits that keep you on track with those goals. the gizmos are just novel tools that can help and provide inspiration for new ideas. learn where you can incorporate the ones you like and nix the rest. changing your mindset and thinking more positively about the things you are doing will inevitably be more helpful, if not just to curtail stressors.

title: 5 Essential Tips for Long-Lasting Productivity
split_comments: here are the 5 things i took away from this video:first, a quote: " if you can learn to enjoy the journey, if you can learn to have fun, then productivity takes care of iteself "tips:1. change your mindset - think to yourself "this will be fun" or "i get to do this" instead of "i have to do this"2. turn it into a game - how can you track your progress in a metric you have direct control over? how else could you gamify this task?3. do it with friends - either find ways to involve them in the project that makes it enjoyable and worth their time, or simply find a pleasant space to do work together4. craft a pleasant working environment - incorporate a pleasant aroma, clean workspace, organized materials, good lighting, your favorite beverage, headphones, music if you choose, and the tools you need within reach5. understand why you are doing the thing you are doing - how does it fit into an overall bigger part of the project? how does it help serve a higher purpose? how will it help you move closer toward one of your goals or objectives?that's all. i hope you find this helpful. cheers!

title: 5 Essential Tips for Long-Lasting Productivity
split_comments: as i am in the process of writing my own book based on the time management trainings i have developed and delivered, i'll share just a few extremely powerful thoughts:  first, 'productivity' has absolutely nothing to with 'getting more things done'. (this a wide misconception, as vast numbers of people fill their lives with mountains of busy work, only to wind up with little to show for it.) secondly, productivity has little to do with 'doing what is important'. (one's list of 'important' to-do's' is potentially infinite. therefore, attempting to work through that list can also be potentially futile.) the key to true productivity is to begin to view time as a resource you are perpetually being forced to invest. you do not have a choice, one way or the other, as to whether, or not, you will invest your time. you will, as long as you are alive. you only have a choice regarding where you invest it. therefore, a sober and honest assessment of what your potential return on investment is likely to be should start to dictate how and where you spend your time. a good empowering question to ask is, "how is this action related to the fulfillment of my highest values and goals?" if something doesn't support your highest values, and the actual achievement of goals that are aligned with those values, you may want to question if it is an investment worthy of your time.

split_comments: appreciate the content a lot! though if you are like me and too many systems confuse you.. here are my two cents.i am an ivy league mba passout. we were taught to make fancy models and steps so we can charge our clients more but when i opened my school in india and italy and saw something else working better with my students.. something way simpler: we aren't productive and waste time because we don't have a good "connection" with ourselves and our goals.we just do many things without really thinking about them. what we need is to spend some time with ourselves everyday planning the next day. best way is to have a walk alone thinking about things to do tomorrow. visualize and make that connection. you'll also move a bit that will release the right hormones for you to have a positive connection with the next day's purpose!!so.. just have a walk and visualise. and thank me later. best of luck guys!!

title: How I Organize My Life - The "LAZI" Productivity System
split_comments: @ali abdaal, nice video! but i was just wondering something when you talk about google drive as your (primary, central) cloud storage for (all of) your files in your video. do you also regularly make backups of your files and folders onto an offline storage drive, e.g. a protected (i.e. encrypted) external usb/hdd/ssd? being a dutch and, also, an eu citizen, we’re getting more and more aware of the security and privacy concerns of having your files and (meta)data stored in the cloud, like those of google, microsoft or apple. i always apply the 3-2-1 rule: always have three identical copies, of which the 1st copy is, in fact, your primary, 'production' copy (whether it is your preference to have your files stored on your device locally or just solely in the cloud), and the 2nd and 3rd are both (identical) backups, yet, separated physically and independently (i.e. literally on different locations, e.g. one on another cloud or a nas, and the other on an offline, external drive with sufficient protection/encryption).

split_comments: note summary: l - lash: the whip that tells ali what hes doing, use calender and time blocks to make sure you are doing what you're supposed to be and for remindersa - agenda: "might-do list" - daily lists of tasks he can do at some point but not a "must do" + one daily highlight that, if completed, marks the day as a "success"z - zettelkasten: a slipbox note system, using roam research note taking app. "morning dump" exploring whatevers on his mind and dumping it on the pagei - inventory: stores everything on google drive + evernote (archive system)

title: How I Manage My Time - 10 Time Management Tips
split_comments: i've been struggling with just finding time to take care of myself. if i wrote down everything i do in a day (which is a great place to start when figuring out just where your time goes and then planning your activities) i realize that i do so much for others. when you're a caretaker and must feed, bathe and support others all day, i don't end up even showering some days, let alone work out. i don't even see the sky for a week sometimes. i don't sleep normal hours and must respond to others in the middle of the night, throwing off my sleep schedule. how can i 'schedule' anything when i'm sleeping until noon because i couldn't get back to sleep after being woken at 3am? i get up and am starving and everyone else wants feeding so i quickly drink my sports shake so i have the stamina to make others their food, first. once that's done, i rush to go do whatever housework or business work i need to do, and a few hours (seems like minutes) it's time to feed everyone, again. it must be nice to be only responsible for yourself. i can't imagine what my life would be like if i didn't have anyone else to deal with - i suppose lonely? or, just busy doing my own stuff? i suppose i have to commit to making breakfasts at night so everyone can feed themselves when they get up. maybe then i could regain my day... lots to think about.

split_comments: man, as a filipino it honestly it makes me kind of sad when you mention the philippines cause of its cheap labor :( i know it's tempting to pay people just 7 usd an hour and feel like you're still doing them a favor, but i can assure you that those people would really appreciate a higher rate if the person hiring them could afford it and especially if they found the work really valuable to them. if you consider the amount of work freelancers have to put in and the structural limitations they experience, i feel it's only fair to try to compensate them fairly for that, not just in relative terms, but in absolute value (or close to it) as well. i know this kind of advice comes from books like the 4-hour work week, but honestly the ideas in that book have a very ruthless, outdated, almost neo-colonial vibe to them. yes, inequalities exist and there's only so much we can do to fix them (to be clear i don't expect ali to fix the problems of the world lol), and more often than not people will choose to take advantage of said inequality if it means making their lives easier. the reality is that that's become a norm, but honestly i wish that wasn't the case. i just worry that this piece of advice is such a recurring recommendation on your channel, especially in a time where people don't just need the bare minimum, but need empathy and any fair valuation of labor they can get. especially considering the fact that developing countries are truly truly struggling to get back on their feet because to the pandemic. i know you don't mean any ill, ali, and are just sharing what works for you. i just hope this kind of advice is delivered with a little more sensitivity or at least not given out without some kind of discussion of these realities. i am a longtime fan of your content and your channel, i just hope this constructive critique reaches you and perhaps serves as some food for thought. wishing you the best, man!

split_comments: here's a 1-second solution. really - it' takes one second. this works to eliminate writer's procrastination effortlessly for both fiction or non-fiction: simply erase part of the last sentence you've written for that day. your mind is hardwired to be working on it, so that you won't be able to wait for the earliest time to get back to writing some more. do this every time. if your last sentence is so golden you don't want to erase it, write another line and erase part of it.\r\rif you're stuck and haven't written in a while, go back to where you left off and erase part of the last sentence you wrote.\r your last sentence might change almost every time. who cares because you're on your way!\r\riow, you've just conquered the biggest challenge to writing for most writers and done it effortlessly.\r\rkelley eidem\rauthor, "the doctor who cures cancer" and "is there a question that heals instantly?"

title: How to Beat Procrastination
split_comments: - ali stopped procrastinating after reading the war of art\r- know the enemy: resistance. fear creates resistance which creates more fear and it becomes an increasingly stronger cycle.\r- the solution is to interpret fear as a signal – fear is your compass. the more scared you are of something, the more important it is to you.\r- become a professional. a pro understands fear and failure is part of the process, they show up to work no matter what, resistance is the daily battle. conversely, an amateur's actions are mood-driven and goals are often extrinsic and hedonic (fun, money and status). \r- hence, also make sure your goals are process goals (i.e. upload 2 videos every week), which are things you can control vs. outcome goals (get 1 mil subscribers) which are nice and to be celebrated but not the point. the point is to trust the process and do the work.

title: How to Beat Procrastination
split_comments: true opinion!!most of the things that he says here are going to make procrastination even worst. he kind of says some point right of course but again to sum up relies heavily on the notion of powering through that resistance.better way to approach procrastination!!if u feel resistance, focus on reducing the resistance and the load factor, not focus on increasing your effort.eg: if i don't feel like working today, its fine, i will just work for 1 hour today.. or 2 hours. u will most likely work longer than that but approach truly like its fine even if u worked just for 1 hour today.reduce your goal and the sense of how well the work has to be. once u reduce this self afflicted burden of setting urself a high goal, the work automatically becomes less intimidatingif the work itself is very twisted and difficult. focus on simplifying it first. focus on the simple stuff. do it first. and for the rest of the work, simplify and make it like manageable list of this and that and that.. the steps that u write be as simple as possible, that aim to detangle the complicated issue into more straighter, manageable steps. you are not a procrastinator the way u approach the work leads u to that feeling of resistance, lighten up ur aim, make it easy for yourself, focus on only task for next 1 hour, make things simpler, ask yourself how can i do this task the most most easiest way...and voila.. see the magic happen.and of course rely on a schedule rather than on motivation.

split_comments: i always keep some juggling balls and a skipping rope nearby. learning to juggle is surprisingly a lot easier that it looks and helps when i'm struggling to overcome creative challenges. the skipping rope is excellent for dealing with physical and mental fatigue and when ever i need to sit down for longer than an hour, i'll set a 20 minute energiser alarm and skip for a a minute or so. if working outdoors,  or in a large space, rallying a football (or something similar) is also a great brain break that fires up the creative juices. start with a rally of.... just one kick.... then work to beat your rally score each time. it's a lot of fun and has helped me a lot :-)

title: How to Beat Procrastination
split_comments: summary for all you scroll-to-the-comments-procrastinators: - ali stopped procrastinating after reading the war of art- know the enemy: resistance. fear creates resistance which creates more fear and it becomes an increasingly stronger cycle.- the solution is to interpret fear as a signal – fear is your compass. the more scared you are of something, the more important it is to you.- become a professional. a pro understands fear and failure is part of the process, they show up to work no matter what, resistance is the daily battle. conversely, an amateur's actions are mood-driven and goals are often extrinsic and hedonic (fun, money and status). - hence, also make sure your goals are process goals (i.e. upload 2 videos every week), which are things you can control vs. outcome goals (get 1 mil subscribers) which are nice and to be celebrated but not the point. the point is to trust the process and do the work.

title: How to Beat Procrastination
split_comments: i am a master's student currently writing my thesis. the reason why i procrastinate is because it's a way for me to escape stress even though deep down i know delaying my tasks will make things worse. during my procrastination period, i noticed a change in my diet and sleeping patterns. i am constantly worrying and thinking about my tasks to the point where i stop enjoying my procrastination. one thing i learned is to never work on my bed. i have to be at my desk to write something meaningful. also, i start scheduling leisure time every day so that when i am done with my task, i feel a sense of accomplishment and reward. its not easy to follow a schedule these days but if i want to be done with my work, i gotta be at my desk everyday! <3

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: last semester with a stockpile of compounded schoolworks i had to work on had to be done dealt with on my part for about 4 weeks. pressure was a goat skull staring at my face and my parents were out dead serious of stopping my schooling due to my unexpected carelessness, so i literally. had. no. choice--but to do my about 50+ small or big intensive and not activities straight from the minute i wake up to 2am in the late morning to finish them before the last quarter ends.result? i literally was the complete opposite of what i always condemned others for, after. for being unproductive in every task i do, failing to integrate that you either upgrade or devolve by what you unconsciously choose to do, not taking in a holistic perspective in approaching daily setbacks, being literally apathetic about where you could end up because of this you'll-get-by attitude that isn't cautios, w/o vision, and plain right indicative of an onset self burying attempt, and whatever.it's the most productive yet extremely numbing thing i've ever done so far, which is still to the affect of me in my couldn't care less state right now. i can't imagine people actually habituating themselves to this, given the imbalance of course.

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: :four_leaf_clover: i have a toxic relationship with productivity too. the past winterbreak moving to 2022, i was in the college dorms alone. i wanted to make sure i was happy and did fun things, and not stress about being productive. i counted the days of my break. there were 27 days, and each day i would post pictures about my day in one post on instagram. it’s like the most story worth moment of the day exercise. it could be as mundane as i ate a snowman cookie from starbucks or reading a book. or literally just a picture of my lunch. i wasn’t aiming for anything big. i just wanted to appreciate each day i had of the break. normally breaks go by too quickly, and i would feel i didn’t do enough. but by counting the days, i inadvertently focused on things that really mattered. at the start of the break my goal was to study blender and cad. by the end i was happy i tried making bread for the first time, and made an origami yoda. ^^ i feel like i started off 2022 very happy because of this, and also connected more with friends as i remembered more interactions each day.

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: :four_leaf_clover:. i can totally relate to this. similar background + a lot going on all at once + bad judge of my own emotional state yada yada. anyway, when i feel overwhelmed and not able to do something wholeheartedly, i take a break and enjoy the break a 100% (be it playing a game/ going out for a cuppa coffee with a friend/ just watching something). that way when i actually get back to work, i feel very refreshed. for me, i get more done within 1.5 hours x 100% focus than 6 hours of guilt-ridden forced productivity. also, one of my mentors asked me to document what i do hourly along with what i am thinking/feeling at that point in time. this helps me be more present in the sense that i kinda know what i am feeling and what i should do in the next hour to change the way i feel (you get the gist ;)).may be the above helps or may be it doesn't. just my two cents.i'll give your solutions a shot too - thanks!anyway, keep them videos coming!  :d \\m/

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: :four_leaf_clover: great video. losing the enjoyment in things that you normally enjoy is one of the hallmarks of depression, which sounds ominous but isn't necessarily. simple things like gloomy weather, inadequate sleep and letting nutrition and exercise fall by the wayside can all have this effect. my psychologist told me she started feeling depressed during covid due to "behaviour activation" not due to actually being depressed as such. basically the change of working from home and not having to get up early or leave the house were behaviours that are normally symptoms of depression. it sounds like your schedule of maybe not eating lunch properly and not sleeping as normal for e.g. could have partly lead to feeling the way you did.

split_comments: it might help to not view your feelings as "something separate" from yourself. and something you need to listen to occasionally. we are our feelings, and our thoughts, so we should let them guide us. which is not the same as becoming an "unproductive couch potato" as i used to think. this has made me less of a productivity-nazi. and the outcome is that i produce a lot better content in less time when i "get around to it and i am driven". i don't force it, which leads to quite extraordinary moments of creativity and off-time. you get to have a break and be productive, in fact, if you don't take enough breaks and you don't "human around" enough i would argue that your work suffers from it :)

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: i resonated with this so closely. i tend to overestimate my ability to do several things in one day with full motivation and energy. goal setting can be a double edged sword is what i’ve come to find. it gets you started well with a morning boost but if by the end of the day, somethings not done, it’s a demoralizing voice that reminds you of your underachievement. it’s also hard when you’ve made productivity a part of your character and stepping away or taking a break kind of flings you into this unknown territory, not being sure who is the real you. i end up questioning whether i trully am this hyper focused and diligent person or that’s just what i tell myself to keep at my work. definitely also working on this. i’ve started by dedicating the first hours  mornings for myself to just get in a good headspace (literally with the headspace app). then when i do get to working, i just set 5 things i’d like to see done by the end of the day and to be content with that. if i do more, cheers, if less, it is what it is. thank you for sharing this glimpse into your emotional state! i’ve been an admirer of your channel for ages.

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: hey ali, great video, love your honesty about this topic! so funny, because earlier this day i was thinking about my productivity system and how i see it:the first step is time management when you start to play with scheduling and then observing and analyzing how things work for you. then you start to notice that it's not all about your time, but about your mood, too. this brings you to step 2, where you start doing mood management. you are trying to find out what & how influences your mood waves. you are working on how to successfully riding your waves of energy and trying to reduce the time when you are in curve dropping, so the drops are smaller and smaller.but then it comes to step no. 3, which i call "holistic productivity". here it's not only about work that has to be done, but connecting all your main "life areas" in a way you feel satisfied. because even if you're productivity ninja during your work time, and then you are too tired to play with your kids, or without the energy for doing something you like, or you just don't feel satisfied with your day before you go to bed, in the long run, you'll become less productive. in this step, we understand we don't need to (or better we're not supposed to be) productive all the time, and be okay with that.i believe the main goal is to find the balance between "working" and "being".wish you all the best!:four_leaf_clover:

split_comments: :four_leaf_clover: i hope i won't get lynched here (i'm sort of afraid i will), i really enjoy the effort you put to the content and have genuine belief that it helps people, but it also can harm. to the matter at hand - i wanted to write something here for a really long time, but now it fits the narrative. i think you would do your audience great favor if you would strongly mention from a time to time that productivity is just not for everyone. i had to learn this the hard way, as the only effect my countless effort had on me were amplifying my self criticism and actually achieving nothing. i had a history with depression, got over it, mustered my life together, applied to hard school, was having fun, but the work was a bit too overhelming i would say and i therefore sought help. sought it here. but somehow (and i'm, ofcourse, not blaming you, this is something fucked up inside my head) the only result i had after trying all the things offered was to just return back to the old inefficient life to actually muster up some results... only now i feel like i'm doing everything wrong and i can no longer appreciate what i loved to do (which was just being goofy around math/physics and having fun while doing it). it is not that my experience has worsened, neither did my ability to percieve the subjects - i actually rationally feel that i have gotten even better at it... but the reward system is broken. next week i'm gonna visit my psychiatrist again for advice how to help myself. from some kind of pressure i got to the point where i emotionally wonder whether i should even bother if it's not efficient and wonder how lucky i will be to finish the school in this mindset.if anyone answers i probably won't answer back since it hurts as fuck and this is about all what i can face right now.have a nice day people, please be kind to yourself and don't overdo tuff just because you have perfectiont's tendencies.it's not worth losing the fun.

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: this is the new culture that is toxic, wanting to constantly be productive in all aspect everything becomes work even though it shouldn’t. you end up putting stuff on a to do list or routine like wake up at 6am workout do morning routine journal and get to work after you’ve finished your work in the evening there’s other stuff that needs to be ticked off even hobbies etc pick up a hobby do it after work etc everything now is a routine. i guess we have picked up this habit from the first lockdown but you honestly don’t need to fill your whole day in with these to do list and check everything off and when you’re not as productive (as humans you can be physically mentally drained and burnt out and need rest) you feel like you’ve achieved nothing that day. you need to see where productivity should lie in your day but soon as you have finished it you need to give yourself a chance to rest not every waking hour needs to be filled with some skill you need to learn.

split_comments: :four_leaf_clover: i have to say, the '3 wins today!' field on my daily check-in has been really helpful in this way.  no matter what my day has been, i have to dig around in my memory and come up with 3 things that made my day a win...and then i start to feel like those things were worthwhile - and my day was worthwhile - and actually i'm a person whose daily output amounts to something real.  this starts a capability spiral - i feel capable, so i'm more fearless about tackling the next day's things.  the 3-wins field has literally made me more productive, by training my brain toward positive thought patterns, rather than negative ones.  and helping me remember to value myself - which is the best way to get what you want out of your life :)  love and valuing of self cannot be underestimated as a force for change.

split_comments: shamrock! i'm old and cannot figure out how to put a shamrock emoji in a comment. i did watch the entire video, as i often do. this is the first time i've responded to your request to comment if i watched the whole thing. here's why--i've been worried about you and i'm glad to hear that you've taken steps to take care of you, and that you recognize this productivity thing can be a monster sometimes. while i'm here, i'm also going to say (though you'll never see this buried in the thousands of comments), i think i heard you say in a video that you heard the health insurance system in the u.s. was not as bad as you first believed. it's bad! the new prez is helping a bit, extending sign-up time for affordable care act insurance, but it is bad. i am blessed in that i and/or my spouse have had an employer who provided us with insurance our entire adult lives. my sister never did (dead now). and she rarely qualified for medicaid (federal insurance for the poor). she was among the "working poor" whose income was too high to qualify for medicaid but too low to afford health insurance. i didn't live the nightmare, but i watched it. so if you come here for a residency or fellowship, know that it's bad. also, i work at a medical school and know lots of entrepreneurial physicians, so get in touch if you'd like an introduction. good luck whatever path you choose!

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: i know this feeling so very well. it comes from having promised yourself two very separate lives that can’t really coexist. when you were at your day job you thought about how much more productive you would be if only you could work full-time on youtube. you also likely daydreamed about how relaxing and free your day would be to have a lie in or be able to choose your own schedule. these are opposites. the truth is you will never be as productive with your time as when you worked a day job and had a solid focus on the small few hours you had control over. as much as you loved that level of productivity it required a level of energy that wasn’t sustainable and you dreamed of getting a break from. this now leaves you unhappy with your level of productivity as you are free to do less but still unsatisfied that you are not achieving more. you are also now getting backlash from the part of your mind that you promised would be allowed more of a rest. you will resent the things that you have to get up for as your body says “i was promised this life would be more restful and it’s not”. that is the start of burn out. when your mind says no to the work you genuinely want it to do and simple tasks feel heavy. the way around this is by recognising that one desire pulls you away from the other. stop expecting both the most productive day & the most fun day at the same time. you cannot achieve hard work & relaxation on the same day. balance can be found by having structured task focused hard-working early-start days that satisfy the productivity level you want. challenge yourself to hit an ambitious outcome that is exciting, with the promise of a full rest afterwards. then follow this up with several zero work, fun only, guilt free wasteman days. it creates a cycle of work & reward that is more in harmony and is more sustainable. it fulfils both needs without them competing. you owe yourself a backlog of those rest days first.

split_comments: hey ali! 1st time commenting here. i think your past few videos clearly reflected the lack of passion and inspiration (your face betrays more than you possibly fathom) and i was one among many who either didnt bother clicking them or stopped watching them past the 2nd minute. having that said, keep 2 things in mind: 1) i'd rather watch 1 video per month from you rather than 8 videos where you clearly dont have fun. your content is not the thing that essentially makes your videos interesting (or at least only partly),  but it is your presentation and fun that infuse it with exuding interest and render it relatable or convincing or interesting in the first place. in other words, scarcity hurts your stats way less than you having no fun. 2) i have watched 90% of your videos thus far, ever since the beginning. from an ipad reviewer, you have grown to a productivity guru (and by far the most likeable of them too in my rather firm opinion), and so, even if unwillingly, you now possess  an influencer role. that means that your reflections about toxic productivity (stuff that is not limited to "mere tips" and theories), about the essence of productivity itself, the things that actually bother you in your everyday life, bother us, interest us and concerns us all far more than any just use-oriented videos. so please embrace your influencer status and talk freely and openly about whatever you actually wanna share.hope you take your time and read it.a longtime fan and supporter,angel

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: :four_leaf_clover: coincidentally, i was just pondering the balance between consulting my thoughts and feelings when it comes to productivity. i've noticed that when i'm more tuned into my feelings, i tend to not be as productive, but when i'm more tuned into my thoughts, i'm more productive and less in tune with my feelings. i posit that when we come to this dilemma, we should pause for a brief moment and think about how doing something/not doing something will impact our future and prioritize our thoughts and feelings accordingly. that way we can decide whether we care enough to get something done or put it off for another time. i suppose that this will lead to overcoming the activation barrier in getting started for some tasks, but will also give us the clarity to do things that truly align with what we desire and not what we're forced to do.

split_comments: hey guess who’s human! welcome to the realisation :)let’s makes some notes whilst you chat - just freeform here ;)1) indistraction is what is making you go to bed late - we all do it! - sure you’ve read the book by the chap who wrote hooked.2) i like the drop down of your number of videos - they dont need to be bangers - the old axiom less is more works in its own right. i also think that people who reinvent themselves regularly become far more rounded people and improve not only their own chances of avoiding fatigue from over exposure both to yourself and to your viewers. citibank are having zoom-free fridays as everyone has meeting fatigue. 3) pushing through, despite physical / emotional  tiredness is doable for important things and life changing goals but long term messes you up - trust me im also an nhs consultant and saw the burnout of many trainees over the years.4) calendly? nice idea for your worshippers - bad for you. this is where your assistant needs to filter more for you. nice admission of your wood-for-the-trees moments - my favourite phrase has been used loads - to do well you need to fail again and again and again.5) dont lose that ability to be a people person - it makes such a difference and will make your life better in the long run. your 50k new subs each month will keep you in demand dont worry. .6) people bang on about this but a general daily ten secs of gratitude to the universe and to yourself in the mirror keeps the spirit alive:four_leaf_clover:

split_comments: interesting what you said about deciding to be happy with what you have done in the day. like you mentioned about how you underestimated the time it take to do things. i think these thing are probably tied. we might feel unhappy with what we have achieved because of how we under estimate the amount of time things take to complete. so we will probably feel happier if we "over estimate" (or more accurately estimate) the amount of time it take to complete a task. and then we will more often hit our goals and be happier in general. we use a process at work called agile which is geared around estimating work and refining over time how we work until we know how much work we can a achieve in a set period. maybe worth looking into and modifying for personal use.

title: My Toxic Relationship With Productivity
split_comments: :four_leaf_clover::four_leaf_clover::four_leaf_clover:this was a video i needed to watch. lately i’ve been kicking myself for not being ‘as productive’ as i would like. i’m working to build routines and time-blocks to manage my time and resources more effectively, and the progress seems to be frustratingly slow going. i have this expectation that i’ll be some sort of productivity master by the end of the month. which i know isn’t any good- but that’s where my mind falls. i know for a fact that my discipline could still use some work. knowing when to tell myself (and others) ‘no’ and not feel like a bad person for doing it. in all honesty i’m just trying to cobble together something that will help me become a little less of a ‘waste-man’. my mind often swims with so many possibilities with how i can or should spend my time that i end up stalling out and doing nothing, procrastinating till a deadline and cramming to do the best i can. i occasionally have little tastes of what it feels like to be ‘productive’- and then i feel like i take a dip straight after. i’m trying to create a system that’s roughly level, while still being ‘higher performing’ than i’m at right now. because i know i can do better. it’s just that right now, i feel as though i’m probably focusing more on output goals than input goals- i always have been, honestly. at least up until recently. as an over-achiever i was always more set on the prize at the end rather than the process of how i get there- it’s a hard habit to break. but i’m doing it one step at a time. this video was the reminder i needed not to let myself dive too far down the opposite direction and to just, be kinder to myself. that was needed, for sure. so thank you, ali. it was truly appreciated.

work, illustrating its relevance beyond creative fields.04:41 :card_index_dividers: introduces the code framework for building a second brain: capture, organize, distill, express.05:09 :brain: shares title: How to Organise your Life - Building a Second Brain
split_comments: when you free up your brain from remembering, enhancing thereby the work memory, you would think you have less stress and be able to focus on creating ideas. that's exactly what will happen, in fact, it will be so good that you start to produce tons of ideas. but then, eventually, there will be more ideas to act upon than there is time, meanwhile new ideas keep stacking up. then eventually one ends up with the same amount of stress multiplied by at least ten times, because of brain explosion instead of brain implosion. so next stop, for me at least, is to optimize the organizational structure, but while doing that, even more new clever ideas still keep stacking up. \r\rconclusion: in the end, the true way to survive is to have great ability to put things really into perspective and do lots of self-reflection. even while i'm now trying to reduce the amount of information i myself produce, i still keep producing new information trying to figure out and understand how to actually do that.\r\rgreat video's, i'm prioritizing your channel for my productivity blueprint.

split_comments: thank you.  have had problems organizing and finding info for over 30 years.  i've been keeping journals with index system for many of those years, especially mind maps (taught this subject for last 20 years).  i knew i had an organizing challenge and have been trying various electronic means.  tried roam for the past year...too complicated for me.  i tried apple notes but found that my volume max it out and according to apple crashed a few times.  sometimes i want to take a picture of a page or two, then write some attaching notes, so i tried liquid text but didn't serve my purpose as well.  questions:  how do you keep all the different app notes?  i'm trying onenote now.  i know i need to change my notebook titles, section and pages (this was helpful in your video, so thank you).  my variety of reading topics is too wide, i now realized i need to reduce those.  i am a author so i collect areas to teach my writing classes, personal development for my coaching clients, articles, maybe a book in the future.  so i've labeled my onenote notebooks with these in mind.  too broad.  would appreciate how to table the topics to find easier.  i have started using mindmanager software again (stopped for five years) and want to again map my notes.  again the challenge, labeling in order to find again.  i love you're labeling "second brain" and i am going to get the book to read, subscribed, and look forward to watching your other videos.  i didn't think i could get used to how fast you talk but after a few minutes i caught on but do wonder if this is the way you talk in real life or you sped up the video (lol).  again "thank you".

title: How to Organise your Life - Building a Second Brain
split_comments: i'm an old man now, but i"ve keep notes from everything i"ve read since just after high school. in college i took a look at my high school notes and realized i had trouble reading my own handwriting. so i retyped all my notes. at the end of each college semester i started going through my notes for each class, boiling them down what seemed useful (or forgetable) and typed those as well. it wasn't until later in college that i realized i could not use many of my notes in papers because i did not collect where it came from for a citation, and fixed that for the future. i still have my original little notebook, which became 3 little 3-ring binders. i switched to composition notebooks where i captured notes, and later maybe 3-4 times per notebook i would type of the notes i wanted added to my digital collection. when i learned how to use google drive and docs, i decided to share my notes with my peers and still to this day offer that link freely. funny though, few have offered to share their collected knowledge. i suspect i will continue doing this until the very end. i look forward to tiago's book, and enjoy your videos. if i don't seem to find a nugget in each one, it's pretty close to a 1:1 ratio. great presentations. the topics have substance. the tempo is good, also i too often speed up what i listen to unless i"m focussed on taking notes. thank you, and keep it up.

title: How to Organise your Life - Building a Second Brain
split_comments: i basically had no work experience but ended up a product manager in a very short period of time and it was really overwhelming. as someone who suffers from adhd, work is usually a blend of creative ideas, bugs to track, changes to test, things to discuss with your team and all those little things that are absolute nightmares for people like me. making a habit of writing things down is the only thing that helped me avoid constant forgetting. i still get overwhelmed sometimes this system helps me pickup where i left off.\xa0i want to add that no matter what software you use, you need to revisit your notes every week remember stuff that you probably forgot, otherwise you're just writing down an endless list to never be acted upon. i use asana for work and notion for my personal notes, plus fig-jam by figma for all the flows and maps that need to get out of my brain and be shared. i also use calendar reminders for daily habits that i still struggle with and that is work in progress, but technology utilised in the right way can definitely help adhd folk have smoother lives.

title: How to Organise your Life - Building a Second Brain
split_comments: introduction to video ( summary of the video)\r\rwrite the things down and form a second brain\r\rany interesting idea you get or a thought note it down\r\rtake in the information and process it and then produce output. \r\r*code* system to organize your life\r\r1. capture it!\r\rbrain is for having ideas and not storing them\r\rany worthy thought you come across or a high yield quote , note it down\r\r1. organize\r\rdon't organize notes topic wise. for eg when taking notes on “how to live longer” or from a random self help book, rather than making separate folders on the note app , try to put them in a folder which is target oriented towards a particular goal\r\rdon't be organization maniac when it comes to organizing your notes. keep it simple so that you would actually access them in future without any effort involved\r\r1. distal it !\r\rwhatever notes you have taken , now actually go through them and make a sort of mental model. apply the information learnt in a target oriented manner. say you want to learn biochemistry. rather than saying that i would study biochem today , say “i will learn how sodium potassium pumps work in cell membrane”. this way you are actually learn for application world. \r\r1. express\r\rall the things captured by you is worthless unless you bring it out to people. express your ideas to public and add value from their learnings to your life to your second brain.\r\rthat was a cute little summary by me. i hope you like it

title: 7 Actionable Ways to Achieve More in Life
split_comments: :bullseye: key takeaways for quick navigation:00:00 this video discusses actionable tips from the book "someday is today" by matthew dicks, offering practical advice for achieving more in life.01:09 tip 1: embrace the "parking lot practice" - true productivity doesn't have to look pretty; don't wait for the perfect environment to pursue creative work.03:58 tip 2: adopt the "minutes mindset" - value every minute, leapfrogging between tasks rather than focusing solely on hours, maximizing productivity in short timeframes.06:50 tip 3: use the "lily pad method" - break down overwhelming goals into smaller tasks, jumping between them based on your mood and energy, fostering flexibility and progress.09:42 tip 4: embrace the "horizon habit" - set directional goals on the horizon instead of overly specific goals, promoting flexibility and resilience in achieving long-term aspirations.11:22 tip 5: beware the "piano precedent" - five-year plans can invite unexpected challenges; find a balance between planning and adapting to life's twists and turns.12:31 tip 6: consider the "100-year-old plan" - when at a crossroads, imagine advice from your 100-year-old self to prioritize what truly matters, providing a broader perspective on decision-making.13:56 tip 7: embrace the "purposeful approach" - productivity isn't just about work; define "soft goals" that bring meaning and satisfaction to your life, allowing time for what truly matters.made with harpa ai

title: 7 Actionable Ways to Achieve More in Life
split_comments: :pill: parking lot practice\r- productivity doesn't have to look pretty.\r- the importance of seizing any moment for creative work.\r- waiting for the perfect environment can lead to prolonged inaction.\r- the timing is never perfect; the time to act is now.\r\r:pill: minute's mindset\r- values every minute, not just every hour.\r- the idea of waiting for specific blocks of time and encourages intentional use of shorter periods.\r- emphasis on the value of small, intentional actions in achieving long-term goals.\r\r:pill: lily pad method\r- encourages a non-linear approach to achieving goals.\r- breaking down tasks into "lily pads" allows for flexibility and progress even when feeling overwhelmed.\r- working on multiple projects simultaneously for flexibility and joy in the creative process.\r\r:pill: horizon habit\r- as an alternative to smart goals, focusing on what is within one's control.\r- setting goals that are realistic and relevant to one's journey prevents demotivation from factors outside of personal control.\r- demotivating nature of goals tied to external metrics (ex, youtube subscribers).\r- encourages setting goals that align with personal growth and progress rather than external measures of success.

title: 7 Actionable Ways to Achieve More in Life
split_comments: 1. productivity in not pretty.2. the minutes mindset - get the most out of every minute.productivity tool - year at a glance.3. the lilypad method - the only real failure for any creator is to stop making stuff. example - works on 5-6 books in parallel(which is the project i feel most pulled right now to be working on?) a) when it comes to pursuing my goals, how might i be able to start in the middle rather than in the beginning?b) when i feel overwhelmed by a particular task, can i leapfrog it and do something else that takes me towards my goals?4. the horizon habit smart = specific, measurable, attainable, realistic, time bound. setting horizon goals - freedom, resilience.5. the piano precedent - five year plans are inviting the universe to drop a piano on you.6. the 100 year old plan - what advice would my 100 yaer old self give to me right now?7. the purposeful approach a) what are the soft goals that you want to aim for in your life?b) what are the thinks that someone else might not consider productive but for you, it's very intentional, satisfying, and fulfeeling?

title: 7 Actionable Ways to Achieve More in Life
split_comments: my takeaway :star:!!!!1.  productivity is not pretty: overcome ideal environment dependency, e.g., the parking lot story.2.  embrace the minutes mindset: get the most out of every minute, like when you are waiting at a restaurant.3. the lily pad method: tackle your projects in a non-linear fashion by working on any part you feel like at the moment to maintain momentum and reduce overwhelm.4. plan with horizon goals: goals are just destinations; they shouldn't be a source of stress. this also leads to the idea that horizon goals, such as becoming a writer and doing other billion things related to writing, give you both freedom and resilience.5. five-year plans are inviting the universe to drop a piano on you: when you plan everything, it's bound to have something go wrong. you have your plans on one axis and fate on the other, and the path your life takes is sort of somewhere between these two lines. so, think of plans as these dots on a chart that you will sometimes touch upon.6. the solomon project: spend time journaling with your older self to reflect on what matters to you, to reveal what you want your legacy to be, and your long-term plans.7. the purposeful approach: be productive for the sake of maximizing fun, work, and relationships. don't just think of it in terms of economic output.thank you ali for your enlightening content. following you since 2020:blue_heart:

title: 7 Actionable Ways to Achieve More in Life
split_comments: summary\r1. *the parking lot practice*: don't wait for the perfect environment to work on your creative projects. take action despite imperfect conditions, and don't let the lack of an ideal setting hold you back.\r\r2. *the minutes mindset*: embrace shorter periods of time as opportunities to be productive. use those small pockets of time during the day to make progress on your goals instead of waiting for longer, uninterrupted hours.\r\r3. *the lily pad method*: instead of tackling your goals sequentially, consider them as lily pads, and jump between them based on your motivation and energy levels. this approach allows for flexibility and prevents feeling overwhelmed.\r\r4. *the horizon habit*: set horizon goals rather than overly specific ones. these are directional goals that provide flexibility, allowing you to adapt and pursue different avenues within a broader focus.\r\r5. *the piano precedent*: when faced with choices, consider what advice your 100-year-old self would give. this perspective helps you prioritize meaningful experiences and relationships over immediate productivity.\r\r6. *the purposeful approach*: productivity doesn't always have to relate to work or economic output. identify "soft goals" that bring you personal satisfaction and meaning, even if they may not appear productive to others.\r\r7. *the 100-year-old plan*: imagine yourself at 100 years old to gain long-term perspective and make decisions that align with your future self's advice, focusing on what truly matters in life.

title: How to Be Effortlessly Disciplined: 5 Mindset Shifts
split_comments: :books:pre-order my book to get an exclusive ticket to the feel-good productivity annual planning workshop!  'the "discipline" thing in the first minute romanticizes what discipline actually means. discipline is not willpower.if you have something in your mind that is distracting you, you don't "discipline" yourself into ignoring them.you fix those distractions. you build routines to guide yourself towards focus.

title: How to Be Effortlessly Disciplined: 5 Mindset Shifts
split_comments: forget the forceful, white-knuckled grip,\rthere's a smoother way to make your willpower flip.\r\rali abdaal, a doc turned busy bee,\rsays chasing hard after discipline might not set you free.\rhere's his recipe for effortless might,\rfive science-backed ways to make your actions take flight.\r\rpicture perfect:  see your future bright,\rthen look at your now - the contrasting light\rwill spark a fire, and ignite the fight.\rimagine your goals, then contrast with today,\rthe gap will propel you, and show you the way.\r\rif-thens for the win:  set plans that click,\rfor when distractions and roadblocks nick\ryour focus and flow. an example, you see,\r"if i lose my focus, i'll take a quick walk, then be\rback at my task, refreshed and on track, you see?"\r\rfriction reduction:  make your path smooth and clear,\rless effort required to banish your fear.\rgym clothes laid out, ready to wear,\rtaking on challenges becomes a breeze to bear.\r\rtrack your attack:  progress in sight,\rkeeps you on fire, burning ever so bright.\rsee yourself winning, improving each day,\rthe thrill of accomplishment will light your way.\r\renjoy the ride:  when tasks become fun,\rdiscipline fades, a race well-run.\rlisten to music that makes your heart sing,\rfind a study spot that joy can bring.\r\rso ditch the struggle, and instead embrace,\rthese effortless methods to find your winning pace.

title: How to Be Effortlessly Disciplined: 5 Mindset Shifts
split_comments: the video is about how to be effortlessly disciplined.\r\rthe speaker, ali abdaal, who is a doctor turned entrepreneur and the author of feelgood productivity, argues that focusing too much on discipline might not be the best approach. instead, he proposes five science-backed methods to develop effortless discipline:\r\rmental contrasting: this involves visualizing your desired future state and contrasting it with your current reality. this discrepancy between where you are and where you want to be is supposed to motivate you to take action. for example, imagine yourself achieving your fitness goals and then contrast that with how you feel now.\rimplementation intentions: this method involves setting up if-then statements to deal with obstacles that might come in your way. for instance, if your goal is to write more, you can set up an if-then statement like "if i get distracted while writing, i will get up and do a quick walk around the room and then come back and start writing again."\rreduce environmental friction: this means designing your environment to make it easier to be disciplined. for example, if you want to go to the gym more often, lay out your gym clothes the night before so you can easily put them on in the morning.\rmonitoring and tracking: tracking your progress can be a great motivator. seeing yourself improve over time will give you a sense of accomplishment and make you want to keep going. there are many apps available to help you track your habits.\rmake it enjoyable: when you enjoy what you’re doing, you’re less likely to need discipline. try to find ways to make boring tasks more fun. for instance, you could listen to upbeat music while you study or find a pretty coffee shop to work in.

title: How to Be Effortlessly Disciplined: 5 Mindset Shifts
split_comments: google bard summary about this video: :eyes:the video is about how to be more disciplined. the speaker, ali abdaal, who is a doctor turned entrepreneur, introduces five science-backed methods to achieve this goal.the first method is mental contrasting, which involves contrasting your present reality with your desired future to create a sense of urgency and motivation. the second method is implementation intentions, which involves creating if-then statements to plan how you will overcome obstacles that might hinder you from achieving your goals.the third method is reducing environmental friction, which involves designing your environment to make it easier to do the things you want to do and avoid the things you don't want to do. the fourth method is monitoring and tracking, which involves tracking your progress to stay motivated and make adjustments as needed.the fifth method is finding ways to make what you're doing more enjoyable or energizing. this can involve incorporating play, power, and people into your activities to make them more fun and engaging.overall, the video emphasizes that discipline is not about willpower, but about creating systems and habits that make it easier to do the things you want to do. by following these five methods, you can become more effortlessly disciplined and achieve your goals.

title: How to Be Effortlessly Disciplined: 5 Mindset Shifts
split_comments: 7:35 when i started keeping my laptop on my bed with the one task i was going to start with that day opened, it reduced so much friction. my adhd brain didn't have to gear up and override the inertia to actually start.i didn't have to convince myself to get out of bed or debate which project to start first when everything feels urgent.i paired "waking up" with "opening my laptop," so it became a context-independent habit that i don't have to think about, and i'm completely thrown off if i don't have my laptop wherever i am. :face_with_tears_of_joy: (it's debatable whether that's healthy, but it helped me to not waste the day being anxious about work but being too much in a freeze mode to actually work.)

split_comments: :bullseye: key takeaways for quick navigation:00:00 :thinking_face: being disciplined is the ability to do hard things you don't want to do. it's like developing an armor for your mind, leading to freedom.01:12 :rainbow: mental contrasting: contrasting your current state with the vividly imagined future goal enhances discipline. visualize obstacles and the desired outcome to boost energy towards goals.04:31 :brain: implementation intentions: planning "if-then" statements for potential obstacles increases goal commitment. combining mental contrasting with implementation intentions is a powerful strategy.06:37 :house: reduce environmental friction: design your environment to make disciplined actions easier. for example, place gym clothes in view or avoid buying unhealthy snacks to align your surroundings with your goals.08:03 :bar_chart: monitoring and tracking: regularly monitoring and measuring progress increases motivation, provides a feedback loop, and offers clarity on what works. the act of measurement itself can lead to improvement.09:57 :grinning_face_with_smiling_eyes: enjoyable and energizing: make tasks more enjoyable to reduce the need for discipline. incorporate elements of play, power, or connect with people to make the process more enjoyable and less daunting.made with harpa ai

title: How to Be Effortlessly Disciplined: 5 Mindset Shifts
split_comments: - :brain: **mental contrasting**:   - contrasting fantasies about a desired future with reflections on present reality induces a necessity to act.  - visualize future goals and contrast them with current obstacles to mobilize energy towards goal commitment.- :robot: **implementation intentions**:  - create "if-then" statements to overcome obstacles.  - example: "if distracted during practice tests, then take a quick walk around the room and resume."- :globe_showing_europe-africa: **reduce environmental friction**:  - design your environment to make discipline easier.  - example: place gym clothes where visible to make it easier to go to the gym.- :bar_chart: **monitoring and tracking**:  - what gets measured gets managed and improved.  - tracking progress provides motivation, feedback, and clarity.- :grinning_face_with_smiling_eyes: **make it enjoyable or energizing**:  - incorporate play, power, and social elements into tasks.  - find ways to make activities more enjoyable, reducing the need for discipline.

title: How to Be Effortlessly Disciplined: 5 Mindset Shifts
split_comments: if you're short on time, here's a quick summary of the valuable information ali shared in this video!1. mental contrasting. recognizing the difference between our current state and our desired state makes it easier for us to act in ways conducive to reaching our goal.2. implementation intentions or habit-stacking. obstacles are bound to arise; developing a tangible plan for overcoming foreseeable challenges is a great way to keep moving.3. environment design. whether you are having trouble dieting or getting work done, create an environment that moves the marker in your direction. a typical example would be keeping candy out of your house if you're trying to eat healthier.4. time management and tracking. tracking our behavior is eye-opening to how we are truly spending our time. it's scientifically proven that by creating a quantitative awareness of our goals, we can increase motivation, create feedback loops, and improve clarity. [bonus: use an app called streaks!]5. make your work enjoyable. getting yourself to do something you know drains your energy is much more work. you can remove friction by adding enjoyable elements to your work; find some way to romanticize your life.hope this was helpful!

title: How to Make 2024 The Best Year of Your Life
split_comments: :pill: method 1: the wheel of life\r- reflect on life in three segments: work, health, relationships.\r- break each segment into three components (e.g., health: body, mind, soul).\r- rate satisfaction or alignment on a scale of 0 to 10 for each component.\r- create a visual representation (radar chart) of the ratings.\r- add a category for joy and rate alignment in actions with joy.\r- identify areas needing improvement and set goals for alignment.\r- regularly use the wheel of life for self-reflection.\r\r:pill: method 2: 12-month celebration\r- imagine celebrating progress in various life areas 12 months from now.\r- identify specific goals for each area, focusing on one primary goal.\r- add the phrase "while enjoying every step along the way" to each goal.\r- write down goals and regularly review them to stay focused.\r- consider the why behind each goal to reinforce motivation.\r- attend a live online workshop on january 6th, 2024, by pre-ordering the book.\r\r:pill: method 3: ideal week method\r- create an ideal week calendar, blocking time for essential activities.\r- determine the time available for personal goals after essential blocks.\r- align personal goals with available time, adjusting as needed.\r- prioritize and allocate time for activities related to the 12-month celebration.\r- embrace flexibility and adapt goals based on available time.\r- attend the live online workshop on january 6th, 2024, by pre-ordering the book.

title: Why You Feel Lost in Life
split_comments: 1. brainstorm what service to the world you’d offer (the north star)    *future ted talk prompt 20 years in the future* - how do you see yourself inspiring people? - don’t overthink it - you can have a couple of ideas. it doesn’t have to be world changing        *the talent service* - if you had all the money and the time, how would you use your talents and skills to serve others? natural talents, skills, strengths    2. reducing your fear    *the fearless dream prompt*    - what would you like to do if you knew you wouldn’t fail - health, work, relationships    - what would you like to do, learn, try, experiment with?    - what impact would you like to have?    - what would you do if you knew you would fail? (what you would learn in the process vibes with you)*the deferred dream prompt*- what’s one dream you’ve always had but never pursued?- why is it a dream for you?- what is stopping you from pursuing it?3. envisioning your dream life - what do you actually value    *the ideal week prompt* - a year from now - create an actual week in calendar- how does it look like? what are you doing? who are you with?        *the future self prompt -* imagine you’ve achieved everything you wanted - how have you changed as a person? what qualities and achievements define this future version of yourself?    4. getting at the issue using other people     - who are the people you most admire and why?    - what quality do they posses that you wish to emulate    - if you were to become an amalgamation of 3-5 people you admire, who would they be, and what would you emulate about them?5. begin with an end in mind    *your funeral* - what would people positively impacted by your work say?        *the obituary writing prompt* - what do you want to remembered for?

title: Why You Feel Lost in Life
split_comments: "know yourself" is an important one. maybe the most important one. and to truly know yourself you need to be able to leave the beaten path and out of your own bottle, as you say it. you have to "lose yourself". i feel that this productivity-, lists-, plans- etc. thing has a lot to do with feeling in control and feeling that you're going somewhere, but it's actually keeping you trapped in the bottle because it's too timid and too rational. i also feel that religious rules do that - they have the purpose to maintain order, but in order to lose yourself you must enter chaos. so what i would say you should do if you feel lost: embrace it and lose yourself even more - it's an opportunity to learn something about yourself, but for that you must be "truly" lost first.

split_comments: :bullseye: key takeaways for quick navigation:00:00 :bullseye: ali abdaal introduces a three-part series on managing time outside of a 9 to 5 job, aimed at helping individuals pursue meaningful activities alongside their regular work.01:38 :hourglass_not_done: time is our most valuable non-renewable resource, emphasizing the importance of effective time management to pursue personal growth and fulfillment.05:12 :memo: prioritization is key: focus on what truly matters by recognizing that you can't do everything, and learn to say no to low-priority tasks.09:38 :counterclockwise_arrows_button: balance life maintenance with progress: allocate time daily for activities that actively move you forward in work, health, or relationships.13:40 :person_in_lotus_position: cultivate intentionality: periodically assess your activities to ensure they align with your intentions, fostering a habit of mindful time usage.14:37 :mantelpiece_clock: intentionality is key in time management; aim for every 15-minute block to be intentional, whether productive or leisure.15:20 :compass: setting goals for the year helps create a sense of progress and purpose beyond daily routines.16:31 :stopwatch: even small blocks of time, like 15 minutes, can be valuable for making progress on important projects or relationships.17:41 :robot: treat yourself like a system; analyze failures or lapses in productivity without self-criticism and adjust strategies accordingly.20:01 :bullseye: *have personal goals outside of work to give purpose to time management efforts; focusing solely on maintaining life's routine isn't fulfilling.

split_comments: here are the five mindsets for managing time outside of your 9-to-5 job:(talked in the video)\r\rtime management is a valuable skill to work on: time is our most valuable non-renewable resource, and spending time learning how to use it better is a valuable skill.\rsee time as your own: if we tell ourselves that we’re bad at time management, we fall into the default of passively consuming entertainment.\ruse your time intentionally: what do you want to achieve in the next 12 months? set some goals and celebrate them.\rembrace the mindset of intentionality: be mindful of how you use your time. ask yourself why things happen and use that information to improve your system.\rhave goals outside of work: having something to work towards outside of your 9-to-5 job will give you a sense of purpose and motivate you to manage your time better.

title: How to Stop Wasting Your Life (Avoid These 5 Things)
split_comments: excellent video!  what prevents people from achieving success is that they do not complete enough high value activities at an productive level on a daily basis.  our days get distracted and wasted so easily that the days just slip away.  the challenge is not just staying focused but knowing:1.  what are your highest level activity you can achieve each day?2.  what process do you have for remembering these activities during the day?3.  how do you attain a level of mastery in these activities that you can perform them well?4.  you have the physical/mental energy to perform these activities along with the strong motivation/dedication.if you can answer the questions above and perform the required task you will be successful over time.

title: How to Stop Wasting Your Life (Avoid These 5 Things)

title: How to Stop Wasting Your Life (Avoid These 5 Things)
split_comments: s made to be addictive and i realised if i let myself watch it for a few minutes, in a week it will turn into a few hours. so i never watch it, and so should you. - this is your life now. its not a detox, its not temporary, so build a system which is sustainable for yourself. for example, i always allow myself watch channels that i am subscribed to, but none of them are addicitive entertainment, they all are educational. find nieches on yt that only inspire you and give you energy and cut the rest. no recommended feed, ever. - limiting time does not work, at all. limit the content instead. its like saying, i will be a crack addict only for 15 minutes a day. if you allow yourself even a little bit, you will have urges all day and dealing with them is stressful. however, if you quit the addictive behavior completely, you will stop feeling this tension overtime. - if your life is empty, it is naturall to fill the void with unintentional  entertainment. you may feel this void very strongly, and it can be painfull in the beginning, and that is great. now, to succesfully replace addictive garbage with real life, slowly start adding real activities: fitness, hobbies, friendship, romance, etc. if you do not, it is going to feel empty and you will be constantly tempted to fall back into addiction.\xa0we all just want to live. all entertainment is an illusory replacement of doing things. you are normal, you have good intentions, but most of us have fallen to this trap, coming from sillicon valley, that made us to believe it is ok to reduce human experience to scrolling. now our responsibility is to get out.i believe in you, best of luck, you really can do this.

title: How to Manage Your Time Outside Your 9-5
split_comments: in brief: the video discusses effective time management strategies, emphasizing the importance of developing specific skills to improve how one manages their time. here's a summary of the key points:\r1. *prioritization:* ali stresses the importance of prioritizing tasks and activities based on their importance and impact on one's goals. he advises against using the phrase "i don't have time" and instead suggests evaluating what activities are truly a priority. practical tips include setting clear goals, utilizing daily adventures to identify the most important task for the day, and conducting weekly reviews to assess and plan priorities.\r\r2. *time blocking:* this technique involves allocating specific blocks of time in one's calendar for various tasks, including work, personal activities, and leisure. ali describes time blocking as a crucial skill for ensuring that important tasks are given dedicated time slots, thus enhancing focus and productivity.\r\r3. *focus:* developing the ability to focus is highlighted as essential for effective time management. ali suggests that improving focus involves practicing single-tasking and reducing distractions. he recommends resources and strategies for enhancing one's ability to focus, such as reading relevant books and participating in focus improvement courses.\r\r4. *follow-through:* the skill of actually doing what one plans to do is discussed as critical for successful time management. ali talks about the challenges of procrastination and the importance of overcoming them through clarity, courage, and starting tasks. he also emphasizes the role of accountability, both personal and external, in ensuring follow-through on commitments.\r\r5. *energizing your work:* finally, ali touches on the importance of finding ways to energize one's work to prevent burnout and maintain high energy levels. he suggests incorporating elements of play, leveraging personal power, and engaging with people to make work more enjoyable and energizing.\r\rthroughout the video, ali provides personal insights, practical tips, and resources to help viewers manage their time more effectively, emphasizing the goal of not just being more productive but also leading a balanced and fulfilling life.gpt4

split_comments: some important points:for more context watch full video1. daily adventure - 1 or 2 most important task for the day.2. time block - important task3. avoid distractions for this daily adventure.4. break a task into chunks and time block accordingly.from my personal experience:1. based on time block use pomodoro yt music, siri for reminding task.2. add widget of google calendar on your mac.3. use box method where at a time focus completely on one part of task..4. most important identify your energy levels throughout the day and plan tasks accordingly. for me morning and evening are best time for doing harder cognitive task. during the noon my energy levels are low and i do task like apply for internships, reply to mails, cook meals for night etc5. make sure to review your week.6. make sure to time block for active recall once in a week if you are students.

title: Why You’re Always Distracted - 5 Mistakes Ruining Your Focus
split_comments: summary :pushpin: planning: lack of a clear plan is a primary cause of distraction. creating a detailed schedule helps in allocating time effectively and avoiding aimless browsing.\r\r:pushpin: emotional awareness: ignoring negative emotions like anxiety, boredom, and self-doubt can lead to distraction as a coping mechanism. acknowledging and addressing these emotions is crucial.\r\r:pushpin: multitasking: attempting to juggle multiple tasks at once leads to reduced efficiency and focus. concentrating on one task at a time enhances productivity.\r\r:pushpin: breaks: productive work is often followed by effective breaks. the most efficient individuals work intensely for about 52 minutes and then take a 17-minute break.\r\r:pushpin: physical well-being: poor sleep, diet, and lack of exercise can impair cognitive functions and focus. maintaining a healthy lifestyle is essential for sustaining concentration.\r\r:pushpin: intentional work: engaging in work with a clear intention and goal in mind fosters traction rather than distraction.\r\r:pushpin: emotional regulation: techniques like 'fast, bad, wrong' can help overcome writer's block and anxiety by lowering the stakes of the task at hand.\r\r:pushpin: making work fun: finding ways to enjoy boring tasks can reduce the likelihood of getting distracted.\r\r:pushpin: attention residue: switching tasks leaves a residue of focus on the previous task, impairing performance on the current task. it's best to complete one task before moving to the next.\r\r:pushpin: health and exercise: a healthy lifestyle supports mental clarity and focus. regular exercise, adequate sleep, and a nutritious diet are foundational to maintaining concentration
